,"1320":"1320","1350":"1350","1408":"1408","1380":"1380","about 1350":"omkring 1350","about 1340":"omkring 1340","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","Wirksworth, Derbyshire, England":"Wirksworth, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1350–1408":"circa 1350–1408","1350–1408":"1350–1408","1350–Female":"1350–Overleden","1380–Male":"1380–Overleden","1320–Male":"1320–Overleden","1320–Female":"1320–Overleden","about 1370":"circa 1370","about 1380":"circa 1380","1320":"1320","1350":"1350","1408":"1408","1380":"1380","about 1350":"circa 1350","about 1340":"circa 1340","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Wirksworth, Derbyshire, England":"Wirksworth, Derbyshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1350–1408":"about 1350–1408","1350–1408":"1350–1408","1350–Female":"1350–Deceased","1380–Male":"1380–Deceased","1320–Male":"1320–Deceased","1320–Female":"1320–Deceased","about 1370":"about 1370","about 1380":"about 1380","1320":"1320","1350":"1350","1408":"1408","1380":"1380","about 1350":"about 1350","about 1340":"about 1340","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","Wirksworth, Derbyshire, England":"Wirksworth, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"GYLES","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Giles  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Giles","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from a medieval personal name, Middle English <i>Giles</i> or <i>Gile</i>, a borrowing from Old French <i>Gil(l)e(s)</i>. This is from Latin <i>Aegidius</i> and this presumably from Greek <i>aigidion</i> ‘kid, young goat’ (alternatively, it could be a Late Latin formation from the Latin personal name <i>Eggius</i> + the suffix <i>-idius</i>). The personal name was widely used in France and the Low Countries, partly through veneration of Saint Gilles de Provence, supposedly a hermit of the 7th century near Arles; he was patron saint of cripples, hence the dedication of Saint Giles Cripplegate in London, though the personal name itself was less common in England than elsewhere in Europe. See also   Gilles  .","Irish: adopted as an Anglicized equivalent of Gaelic <b>Ó Glaisne</b>, a County Louth name based on <i>glas</i> ‘green, blue, gray’.","French: variant of   Gilles  , a cognate of 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert GYLES I was born about 1350, in Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Ralph GYLES I, was 32 and his mother, Mrs. Ralph Gell, was 32. He married Mrs. Robert Gell about 1370, in Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1408, in Wirksworth, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 59."},"et":{"about 1350–1408":"umbes 1350–1408","1350–1408":"1350–1408","1350–Female":"1350–Surnud","1380–Male":"1380–Surnud","1320–Male":"1320–Surnud","1320–Female":"1320–Surnud","about 1370":"umbes 1370","about 1380":"um